' cults as well as nonconformist dimensions of Sufism and fully explicates the reasons for the increasing social prominence of the Sufi mode of piety during this early period in Islamic history.Key FeaturesStrikes a balance between social and intellectual historyIdentifies and articulates questions of interest to scholars, students and general readersConsistently locates Sufism within its broader social and intellectual context"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSufism. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074861918440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862897140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748628971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748628971/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK